EPODE III.

A mock heroic invective against garlic. Horace has eaten some dish seasoned with it at Maecenas’ table, and he treats it as a practical jol-xe of his host's (v. 20 ‘iocose Maecenas ’). ‘Garlic should be sub- stituted for hemlock in the punishment of parricides. What can the reapers' stomachs be made of? He has taken poison—viper's blood, some decoction of Canidia’s—the very drug which Medea used to pre- vent the bulls touching Jason, and to destroy Creiisa. The heat of Apulia in the dog—days, of Hercules’ fiery garment, was nothing to it. If Maecenas has the bad taste to have such a dish again, may he be rewarded by finding that he cannot get a kiss if he wishes itr'
